\p
\v 43 \w Jesus|strong="G3004"\w* \w told|strong="G3004"\w* \w them|strong="G1325"\w* \w strongly|strong="G4183"\w*, “Don’t \w tell|strong="G3004"\w* \w anyone|strong="G3367"\w* \w that|strong="G2443"\w* \w I|strong="G2532"\w* \w made|strong="G3004"\w* \w this|strong="G3778"\w* little girl alive \w again|strong="G2532"\w*.” \w Then|strong="G2532"\w* \w he|strong="G2532"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2443"\w* \w them|strong="G1325"\w*, “\w Now|strong="G2532"\w* \w give|strong="G1325"\w* \w her|strong="G1325"\w* \w some|strong="G3778"\w* \w food|strong="G5315"\w* \w to|strong="G2443"\w* \w eat|strong="G2068"\w*.”   
\c 6  
\s1 Jesus’s own countrymen rubbished him  
\p
\v 1 \w Jesus|strong="G1831"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w his|strong="G1519"\w* \w followers|strong="G3588"\w* \w left|strong="G1831"\w* \w that|strong="G3588"\w* \w country|strong="G3968"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w went|strong="G1831"\w* \w back|strong="G1519"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w his|strong="G1519"\w* \w own|strong="G3968"\w* \w town|strong="G1564"\w*, \w called|strong="G3588"\w* Nazareth.   
\p
\v 2-3 On the Jewish people’s rest day, Jesus went to the Jewish meeting house, and he started to teach the people God’s message. A lot of the people heard his words, and they were really shocked. They said, “How does he know so much? How come he can do powerful things? He’s nobody special. We know him. He grew up here, in this town. His mother, Mary, lives here, with his brothers, James, Joses, Judas and Simon, as well as his sisters. His job here is to make things with wood.” So those Nazareth people got angry, and they wouldn’t take any notice of him.   
\p
\v 4 \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w then|strong="G2532"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w them|strong="G3588"\w*, “\w If|strong="G1487"\w* \w God|strong="G3004"\w* \w gives|strong="G3004"\w* \w a|strong="G2532"\w* \w man|strong="G3361"\w* \w a|strong="G2532"\w* message, lots \w of|strong="G2532"\w* \w people|strong="G1510"\w* \w know|strong="G1722"\w* \w he|strong="G2532"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w God|strong="G3004"\w*’s \w man|strong="G3361"\w*, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w they|strong="G2532"\w* respect \w him|strong="G3588"\w*. \w But|strong="G2532"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w his|strong="G1438"\w* \w own|strong="G1438"\w* \w people|strong="G1510"\w*. \w They|strong="G2532"\w* \w lived|strong="G1510"\w* \w with|strong="G1722"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w man|strong="G3361"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w knew|strong="G3756"\w* \w him|strong="G3588"\w* \w from|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w time|strong="G1722"\w* \w he|strong="G2532"\w* \w was|strong="G1510"\w* \w a|strong="G2532"\w* little boy. \w They|strong="G2532"\w* don’\w t|strong="G3588"\w* respect \w him|strong="G3588"\w*. \w Even|strong="G2532"\w* \w his|strong="G1438"\w* close family \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w relatives|strong="G4773"\w* don’\w t|strong="G3588"\w* listen \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w him|strong="G3588"\w*.”\x * \xo 6:4 \xt John 4:44\x*   
\p
\v 5-6 You see, the people of Jesus’s own town didn’t believe in him, and he was really shocked. He couldn’t do anything really powerful there, because they didn’t believe in him. He only touched a few sick people and made them better. Then he left Nazareth, and went to other towns, and taught God’s word to the people there.   
\s1 Jesus sent out his 12 special workers  
\p
\v 7-11 Jesus called together his 12 special workers. He told them, “You have to go to every town and tell my message to the people. Let them take care of you when you go there. Don’t take a bag, or food, or money, or spare clothes with you. Just take your shoes and a walking stick. After you get to a town, if the people in that town are happy for you to stay there, just stay in one house. Don’t move around to different houses. But if the people in that town don’t want you to be there, and if they will not listen to you, then you have to go away from that town. As you leave it, shake the dirt off your feet. That will show those people that they will get trouble. It will be like you are telling them, ‘You didn’t take any notice of my message, so God will judge you and punish you.’”\x * \xo 6:7-11 \xt Luke 10:4-11; Acts 13:51\x*  
\p And Jesus told his special workers, “I’m giving you my power to force bad spirits out from people.” Then Jesus split them up into 6 teams with 2 men in each team, and he sent them out to do God’s work.  
\v 12 \w So|strong="G2443"\w* \w his|strong="G2532"\w* special workers \w went|strong="G1831"\w* \w to|strong="G2443"\w* \w other|strong="G2443"\w* towns, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w they|strong="G2532"\w* told everyone \w to|strong="G2443"\w* turn around, \w to|strong="G2443"\w* change \w their|strong="G2532"\w* lives, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w to|strong="G2443"\w* \w come|strong="G1831"\w* back \w to|strong="G2443"\w* \w God|strong="G2532"\w*’s way.  
\v 13 \w Those|strong="G2532"\w* men \w forced|strong="G1544"\w* \w a|strong="G2532"\w* lot \w of|strong="G2532"\w* bad spirits \w out|strong="G1544"\w* \w of|strong="G2532"\w* \w people|strong="G4183"\w*. \w And|strong="G2532"\w* \w they|strong="G2532"\w* \w put|strong="G1544"\w* \w olive|strong="G1637"\w* \w oil|strong="G1637"\w* \w on|strong="G2532"\w* \w a|strong="G2532"\w* lot \w of|strong="G2532"\w* sick \w people|strong="G4183"\w*, like medicine \w for|strong="G2532"\w* \w them|strong="G1544"\w*, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w those|strong="G2532"\w* sick \w people|strong="G4183"\w* got \w better|strong="G4183"\w*.\x * \xo 6:13 \xt James 5:14\x*   
\s1 Herod killed John the Baptiser  
\p
\v 14-29 This is the story about what happened to John, the man that baptised people. The big boss over that country was Herod, and his brother was Philip. Philip’s wife’s name was Herodias. But Herodias left Philip, and Herod married her.  
\p John kept on telling Herod, “You are breaking God’s law. You shouldn’t have your brother’s wife.” Herodias hated John for saying that, and she wanted to kill him, but Herod sent some soldiers to grab John and keep him in jail, so Herodias couldn’t do anything to him. John was a good man, one of God’s own men, so Herod respected John, and he was a bit frightened of him too. Herod used to talk with John. He didn’t really understand John’s message, but he liked to listen to him.  
\p Some time later, Herod had a birthday party. All the leaders of Herod’s army, and the government bosses from Galilee country, they were all there at Herod’s party.  
\p Herodias’s daughter danced for them at that party. Herod and everybody else really liked to watch her dance. She made them really happy, so Herod made a strong promise to her. He told her, “I want to give you something really good. You can ask for anything. I will give you anything you ask for, even as much as half of this country. This is true. I’m not lying.” \fig The daughter of Herodias danced for Herod and his friends|src="Bible1519.tif" size="col" ref="6:14-29" \fig*  
\p That young girl went outside and asked her mother, “What will I ask for?”  
\p Her mother said, “Go back in and ask the big boss to send a soldier to cut off John the Baptiser’s head and give it to you.”  
\p The girl ran back into the party and said to Herod, “I want you to give me John the Baptiser’s head on a big plate, and I want it right now.”  
\p When Herod heard her say that, he was really sad. But he didn’t want to break his promise. He didn’t want to feel shame in front of his friends, so he sent a soldier to cut off John’s head, and to bring it back to the girl on a big plate.  
\p The soldier went to the jail, and he cut off John’s head, and he brought it back to the party, and he gave it to the young girl, and then she gave it to her mother.  
\p John’s friends heard the bad news, so they came and got his body, then they took it away and buried it.  
\s1 Herod was worried about Jesus  
\p Later lots of people heard about what Jesus was doing, and they talked about him all the time. Some people said, “Jesus is really Elijah, that old man that told God’s messages a long time ago. God made him alive again.”  
\p Some other people said, “Jesus is a man talking for God, just like those other men that told God’s messages a long time ago.”  
\p But some people reckoned, “Jesus is really John the Baptiser. God made John alive again, and God gave him power to do great things.”  
\p Herod heard those stories, and he said, “I got my soldiers to cut John’s head off, but this man, Jesus, he has to be John the Baptiser. I reckon God made him alive again.”\x * \xo 6:14-29 \xt Matthew 16:14; Mark 8:28; Luke 3:19-20; 9:19\x*   
\s1 Jesus fed more than 5,000 people  
\p
